              <p class="mb-0">We hope to help you with this!</p>
              <p>If a term you are looking for is not included, then simply send it to office@findmyhome.at with a small reference to this legal dictionary - we will then add the definition as soon as possible. Thanks!</p>
              <h5>Definitions of legal terms</h5>
              <!--===================== Terms with A =====================-->
              <div class="a_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with A</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="transfer.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Transfer</a></h6>
                <p>The transfer is a one-off payment that the tenant has to make to the landlord or the previous tenant in connection with the conclusion of the contract.</p>
                <p>In the full application area of the MRG (Tenancy Law) there is a transfer ban.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="description.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Depreciation</a></h6>
                <p>The depreciation of assets is called depreciation in accounting.</p>
                <p>Land is not subject to scheduled depreciation, but buildings are.</p>
                <a href="application_area.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Area of application of the MRG (Tenancy Law) - full area of application / partial area of application / non-application area</a>
                <p>The tenant protection anchored in the MRG (Tenancy Law) has a predominantly mandatory character, so it cannot be contractually changed to the detriment of the tenant. However, only those who fall within the scope enjoy protection.</p>
                <p>Objects in old buildings and subsidized new buildings fall within the full scope of application, and their tenants enjoy comprehensive protection.</p>
                <p>The partial scope of application of the MRG includes rental properties that are rented without public funds due to a rental after June 30th. building permit issued in 1953. With regard to the MRG, only the provisions on grandfathering and tenancy law in the event of death apply to these, but in particular not the regulation on rent.</p>
                <p>The full exemptions from the MRG include rental contracts that are concluded in the context of accommodation or garages, as well as homes, official apartments, second homes or holiday apartments and, since January 1, 2002, rental contracts for one- and two-family houses.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="declaration_eligibility.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Declaration of eligibility</a></h6>
                <p>With the declaration of eligibility in a purchase contract, the person entitled to the property (seller's side) makes a declaration that he consents to the <a href="incorporation.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">incorporation</a> of another person (buyer's side) and thusagrees <a href="land_register.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">to the entry of the buyer in the land register</a> . The declaration of eligibility is a prerequisite for incorporation in the land register.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Furnishing categories</a></h6>
                <p>In the area of application of the MRG (Tenancy Law), maximum limits for rents are set in four categories: A, B, C and D. The classification of an apartment in the respective category is based on the condition of the apartment, the presence of a kitchen, bathroom and toilet as well as the The size of the apartment is decisive.</p>
              </div>
              <!--===================== Terms with B =====================-->
              <div class="b_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with B</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="encumbrance_sale.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Prohibition on encumbrance and sale</a></h6>
                <p class="mb-0">This means that the owner can neither encumber the property (e.g. with a loan or usufruct) nor sell it or give it away without the consent of the beneficiary. The prohibition may, but need not, include both restrictions.</p>
                <p>The ban only becomes effective against any outsider once it has been entered in the land register. However, the ban on sale and encumbrance can only be entered in the land register if it is granted between spouses or between (grand)parents and (stepchildren, in-laws or grandchildren) children.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="operating_cost.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Operating costs</a></h6>
                <p class="mb-0">Operating costs are costs that owners incur when operating a building.</p>
                <p class="mb-0">The Tenancy Law Act (MRG) specifies exactly which costs may be transferred proportionately to tenants. For example, costs associated with maintenance should not be passed on (e.g., in-house repairs).</p>
                <p>The operating costs are divided according to the ratio of the usable area of the respective rental property to the total area of the house.</p>
              </div>
              <!--===================== Terms with E =====================-->
              <div class="e_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with E</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="appraised.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Appraised</a></h6>
                <p>value Appraised value describes the value of a piece of land and the buildings on it. It is determined by the tax office. <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Until the 2015/2016 tax reform,</a> the assessed value servedas the basis for calculating <a href="real_estate_tax.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">the real estate transfer tax</a> . With a few exceptions, the real estate transfer tax is nowcalculated <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">from the real estate value , which is based on the market value</a> – which is significantly higher than the assessed value.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Right of Submission</a></h6>
                <p>Where the MRG is applicable to a lease, the main tenant can assign their right to rent to certain close relatives who have urgent housing needs. The prerequisite is that you have lived with him in the apartment for at least two years</p>
                <p>This rule applies to all relatives in the straight line (i.e. children, grandchildren and parents), spouses and adopted children. Siblings also have a right of entry, but they must have lived in the same household for five years.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Incorporation</a></h6>
                <p>Incorporation (also intabulation) refers to a certain form of entry in the land register. The entry in the <a href="land_register.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">land register</a> causes either an unconditional acquisition of rights or, in the event of deletion, a loss of rights and is a prerequisite for the acquisition of real rights to real estate.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Energy performance certificate / energy efficiency / energy index</a></h6>
                <p>When renting, leasing and <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">selling real estate,</a> an energy performance certificate must be presented. It contains essential information on the thermal quality and energy consumption of a building.</p>
                <p>The energy index f indicates the specific heating requirement. It tells you how much energy a house needs per square meter per year for space heating. The energy index is printed next to the colored scale in the corresponding category.</p>
                <p>The "overall energy efficiency factor" (fGEE) compares the building with a reference object from the building stock from 2007. It can thus be estimated whether the existing property is better (fGEE < 1) or worse (fGEE > 1) in terms of energy.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Euribor</a></h6>
                <p>Euribor is the average interest rate at which a selection of European banks grant each other EURO bonds with different maturities. It serves as a basis for calculating interest on various investment products, such as savings accounts or loans for real estate financing.</p>
              </div>
              <!--===================== Terms with F =====================-->
              <div class="f_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with F</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Usufruct Right</a></h6>
                <p>With a usufruct right, the owner allows another person to use his property without restrictions while preserving the substance. The utility can be either personal use or rental. A usufruct does not have to be entered in the land register, but this gives it effect in rem, i.e. it can be enforced against any (future) owner.</p>
              </div>
              <!--===================== Terms with G =====================-->
              <div class="g_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with G</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Right of use / right of residence</a></h6>
                <p>The right of residence is a personal easement and allows the beneficiary to live in someone else's home. It can be structuredas a right of use or as<a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank"> a usufruct right .</a></p>
                <p class="mb-0">If the right of residence refers to all habitable parts of the house and the person entitled to live in the building may use the building without restriction (e.g. also rent it out), there is a right of usufruct.</p>
                <p>The interpretation of the contract is decisive.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="land_register.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Land register</a></h6>
                <p class="mb-0">The land register is a public directory in which, for example, ownership of a property (including real estate), but also residential property, lien or building rights are recorded.</p>
                <p>It is maintained by the district courts and is open to the public.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="real_estate_tax.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Real estate transfer tax</a></h6>
                <p>The real estate transfer tax levies taxes on the free and non-remunerated movement of domestic real estate. Tax debtors are (at least theoretically) both the transferor and the transferee.</p>
                <p>The assessment basis is basically the value of the consideration (e.g. the purchase price), but at least the value of the property (especially in the case of gifts in the family association). In exceptional cases, for example when acquiring agricultural land, the simple <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">assessed value</a> is decisive.</p>
                <p>The partial scope of application of the MRG includes rental properties that are rented without public funds due to a rental after June 30th. building permit issued in 1953. With regard to the MRG, only the provisions on grandfathering and tenancy law in the event of death apply to these, but in particular not the regulation on rent.</p>
                <p>The full exemptions from the MRG include rental contracts that are concluded in the context of accommodation or garages, as well as homes, official apartments, second homes or holiday apartments and, since January 1, 2002, rental contracts for one- and two-family houses.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Declaration of eligibility</a></h6>
                <p>With the declaration of eligibility in a purchase contract, the person entitled to the property (seller's side) makes a declaration that he consents to the <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">incorporation</a> of another person (buyer's side) and thusagrees <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">to the entry of the buyer in the land register</a> . The declaration of eligibility is a prerequisite for incorporation in the land register.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Furnishing categories</a></h6>
                <p>In the area of application of the MRG (Tenancy Law), maximum limits for rents are set in four categories: A, B, C and D. The classification of an apartment in the respective category is based on the condition of the apartment, the presence of a kitchen, bathroom and toilet as well as the The size of the apartment is decisive.</p>
              </div>
              <!--===================== Terms with H =====================-->
              <div class="h_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with H</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Main rent / sublease</a></h6>
                <p class="mb-0">Main rent exists when the rental contractis concluded <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">with the owner (or usufructuary ) of a property, with the tenant (or lessee) of an apartment building or with the apartment owner. </a>If a rental contract is not concluded with the owner but with the tenant of the apartment, there is a sublease.</p>
                <p>More about this here:<a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank"> Subletting: Subletting despite a ban in the rental agreement?</a></p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Household insurance / liability insurance</a></h6>
                <p>Every resident of a property should have household insurance. It pays for the repair or replacement of damaged items in a household. Whether household insurance pays for the repair of damage depends on whether the cause of the damage is recorded in the policy. You should therefore pay attention to the causes (e.g. storm, burglary, fire, etc.) you are insured against. The more comprehensive the insurance, the more expensive it is of course.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Mortgage</a></h6>
                <p>A mortgage is a lien on an immovable property such as real estate. The right of lien is a right in rem to secure a claim (security function).</p>
                <p>Usually, the credit institution that finances a real estate purchase with the right of lien has the right to access a certain thing belonging to the debtor (e.g. the property) to collect this secured claim (satisfaction function) - if the debtor, for example, makes his repayments within a certain period can no longer afford.</p>
              </div>
              <!--===================== Terms with I =====================-->
              <div class="i_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with I</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Ideal co-ownership</a></h6>
                <p>An item is co-ownership if several people are entitled to the right of ownership. Each co-owner is only entitled to a certain quota (ideal share). In the case of real estate, the term “simple co-ownership” is also common.</p>
                <p>In principle, a co-owner can dispose of his own share alone, but only all co-owners can dispose of the entire thing together. This means that a co-owner can sell his share without the consent of the other co-owners</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="real_estate_tax.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Real estate income tax</a></h6>
                <p>The real estate income tax taxes the profit from the private sale of real estate, which is why only purchase and sale transactions against payment are recorded. The real estate income tax is to be borne by the seller.</p>
                <p class="mb-0">Real estate is not just land, but also buildings (including <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">condominiums</a> ) and rights equivalent to real estate, such as building rights.</p>
                <p>The tax is 30% of the profit made.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Inflation deduction</a></h6>
                <p>The inflation deduction has been omitted since 2016. Until then, the assessment basis for real estate income tax for new properties was reduced by the inflation deduction of 2% from the 11th year.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Maintenance & Repair</a></h6>
                <p>The distinction between maintenance and repair of real estate is essentially of interest for the depreciation of expenses, since different regulations apply to these two aspects.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Intabulation</a></h6>
                <p>Intabulation (also incorporation) is a specific form of entry in the land register. The entry in the <a href="land_register.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Land register</a> causes either an unconditional acquisition of rights or, in the event of deletion, a loss of rights and is a prerequisite for the acquisition of real rights to real estate.</p>
              </div>
              <!--===================== Terms with K =====================-->
              <div class="k_container mt-4">
                <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with K</div>
                <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Cold progression</a></h6>
                <p>In order to understand cold progression, the system of progressive wage and income tax must be understood: income is split – based on legal limits – and each part is charged a different tax rate. The first part is tax-free, the following parts are subject to an ever increasing tax rate.</p>
                <p class="mb-0">Every year the salary is adjusted for inflation (depreciation of money), i.e. it increases nominally (but not in terms of value). If the salary increases due to the inflation adjustment so that you get to the next tariff level, you pay more taxes without actually earning more. This phenomenon is called cold progression.</p>
                <p>In order to avoid the cold progression, the tariff levels must be adjusted annually for inflation.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Deposit</a></h6>
                <p class="mb-0">The deposit is a kind of insurance provided by the landlord for any damage caused by the tenant at the end of the tenancy. The tenant deposits the amount at the beginning of the tenancy with the landlord, who must invest it with interest.</p>
                <p>The tenant may not be held responsible for the usual wear and tear of the rental property.</p>
                <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Right of termination / period of notice / template letter of termination</a></h6>
                <p>A lease can be terminated, that much is clear. When this can happen depends on whether the lease is for a fixed-term or for an indefinite period. In addition, the notice period must be taken into account. The rent must continue to be paid for the duration of the notice period, the property may of course also be used for this period.</p>
                <p>When writing a letter of resignation, some formal structures must be taken into account. For your convenience, we are providing a <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">download of a sample resignation letter</a> in the full post .</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"></a></h6>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with M =====================-->
            <div class="m_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with M</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Rent/rent</a></h6>
              <p class="mb-0">In the classic rental agreement, the landlord lets the tenant use a living space for a limited period of time. In return, the tenant owes the landlord a fee in the form of rent.</p>
              <p>The gross rent consists of the net rent (the actual rent) and the <a href="operating_cost.php" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">operating costs</a> .</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Rent Law Act (MRG) – full scope / partial scope / non-scope</a></h6>
              <p>The tenant protection anchored in the MRG (Rental Law) has a predominantly mandatory character, so it cannot be contractually changed to the detriment of the tenant. However, only those who fall within the scope enjoy protection.</p>
              <p>Objects in old buildings and subsidized new buildings fall within the full scope of application, and their tenants enjoy comprehensive protection.</p>
              <p>The partial scope of application of the MRG includes rental properties that are rented without public funds due to a rental after June 30th. building permit issued in 1953. With regard to the MRG, only the provisions on grandfathering and tenancy law in the event of death apply to these, but in particular not the regulation on rent.</p>
              <p>The full exemptions from the MRG include rental contracts that are concluded in the context of accommodation or garages, as well as homes, official apartments, second homes or holiday apartments and, since January 1, 2002, rental contracts for one- and two-family houses.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Rent reduction</a></h6>
              <p>As a tenant of a property, there are cases in which you have the<a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">right to a rent reduction . </a></p>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with N =====================-->
            <div class="n_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with N</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Ancillary costs when buying an apartment & ancillary costs when buying a house</a></h6>
              <p>In addition to the purchase price, there are other amounts to be paid when purchasing a property: real estate transfer tax, registration fee for ownership rights, registration fee for a lien, entry fee for the land register application, costs for notarial certification, legal and brokerage fees.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Notary</a></h6>
              <p>A notary is a public officer who has been given government authority to draw up public deeds. In contrast to the lawyer, he is non-partisan and non-partisan in his function.</p>
              <p>When buying real estate, the notary is required to certify the signatures on the purchase contract. The costs at the notary depend on the purchase price of the property, the number of signatures to be certified and the number of certifications.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Usable area / floor area / living area</a></h6>
              <p>The living area is the entire floor area that the apartment or the condominium has to offer, i.e. the total floor area of the premises. Areas outside of the apartment or house, such as the basement or storage room, do not count.</p>
              <p>The usable area is the area that can be used for the intended purpose. Traffic areas (e.g. entrances, stairwells, elevators, corridors) and functional areas (e.g. boiler room, machine rooms) are not included.</p>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with P =====================-->
            <div class="p_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with P</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Parification</a></h6>
              <p>The term “parification” refers to the justification of home ownership . This justification of home ownership can only be done for the entire property. This means that there is no coexistence of home ownership and simple co-ownership (a so-called “mixed house”).</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Right of lien</a></h6>
              <p>A right of lien is a right in rem to secure a claim (security function). A lien on an immovable property such as real estate is called a mortgage.</p>
              <p>Usually, the credit institution that finances a real estate purchase with the right of lien has the right to access a certain thing belonging to the debtor (e.g. the property) to collect this secured claim (satisfaction function) - if the debtor, for example, makes his repayments within a certain period can no longer afford.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Commission</a></h6>
              <p>The commission is the real estate agent's fee. If there is a successful conclusion due to his mediation services, he receives a one-off amount for this. For the mediation of rental contracts, the amount is given in a certain number of monthly rents. Depending on the duration and type of tenancy, the commission may not exceed two months' rent.</p>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with R =====================-->
            <div class="r_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with R</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Real division A co-owner can sue for division of the ideal co-ownership</a></h6>
              <p>with the division suit. The result is that the community of owners is dissolved. The division can take place in two ways: civil division (sale of the property and division of the proceeds according to the shares) or real division (also division in kind).</p>
              <p>In the case of developed land, the real division takes place through the establishment of <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">residential property</a> or through the division of the land area. In real division, the co-owners give up their co-ownership rights to the entire property and everyone receives sole ownership of one or more residential properties or a part of the property.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Indicative rent</a></h6>
              <p>In the full application area of the MRG (Tenancy Law), the free agreement of the rent is not permitted. Rather, both the amount of the maximum permissible main rent and what operating costs can be offset are regulated by this law.</p>
              <p>According to the MRG, the maximum rent that can be demanded as the main rent for an apartment is the so-called benchmark rent. The procedure for calculating the benchmark rent is relatively complicated. Based on a reference value, which is to be announced for each federal state by ordinance from the Federal Ministry of Justice, depending on the size of the apartment, equipment, condition and location of the specific apartment, the reference value rent for this apartment is calculated with surcharges and deductions.</p>
              <p>For example, there are deductions for floors without a lift, no basement compartment, above-average noise, poor lighting, on the other hand, for example, surcharges for green areas, quiet areas, existing balconies or terraces, intercoms, washing machine connections, telecable connections.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Right of withdrawal / right of withdrawal for real estate</a></h6>
              <p>Click here for a video that explains the right of withdrawal or the right of withdrawal for real estate.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank"></a></h6>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with S =====================-->
            <div class="s_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with S</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Tax reform 2015/2016</a></h6>
              <p class="mb-0">How the tax reform 2015/2016 affected the purchase, sale, inheritance and donation of real estate can be read in two articles: – Tax reform</p>
              <p class="mb-0">analysis<a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank"> for real estate 2015</a></p>
              <p class="mb-0"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">– Tax reform real estate 2016</a></p>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with T =====================-->
            <div class="t_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with T</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Partial gratuitous / gratuitous transfer</a></h6>
              <p>A gratuitous transfer exists if the propertyis sold <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">for more than 70% of the property's value .</a> If the value of the consideration (e.g. purchase price) is no more than 30% of the property value, there is no payment.</p>
              <p>In between, i.e. if the value of the consideration is more than 30% but less than 70% of the property value, there is a partial purchase.</p>
              <p>However, certain acquisitions are always considered free of charge, eg acquisitions after death through inheritance, legacy or legacies, as well as acquisitions within the family group among living persons.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Action for division</a></h6>
              <p>With the action for division, a co-owner can sue for the division of the <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">ideal co-ownership</a> . The result is that the community of owners is dissolved. The division can take place in two ways: civil division (sale of the property and division of the proceeds according to the shares) or real division (also division in kind).<p>
              <p>In the case of developed land, the real division takes place through the establishment of <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">residential property</a> or through the division of the land area. In real division, the co-owners give up their co-ownership rights to the entire property and everyone receives sole ownership of one or more residential properties or a part of the property.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Trusteeship / trustee account</a></h6>
              <p>The processing of a property purchase by a trustee (lawyer or<a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank"> notary</a> ) means that the purchase price is not transferred directly to the seller, but to a trustee account specially opened for this purchase contract.</p>
              <p>The trustee only forwards the purchase price to the seller if certain conditions agreed in advance (eg <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">incorporation</a> of title) are met.</p>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with U =====================-->
            <div class="u_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with U</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Transfer of tenancy law</a></h6>
              <p>What happens if a landlord sells the property? Can the tenants stay in their apartment anyway? yes they may</p>
              <p>The buyer assumes the role of landlord and enters into all existing leases as such. Nothing changes for the tenants.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Sublease / main rent</a></h6>
              <p class="mb-0">Main rent exists when the rental contractis concluded <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">with the owner (or usufructuary ) of a property, with the tenant (or lessee) of an apartment building or with the apartment owner.</a> If a rental contract is not concluded with the owner but with the tenant of the apartment, there is a sublease.</p>
              <p>More about this here: Subletting: <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Subletting despite a ban in the rental agreement?</a></p>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with V =====================-->
            <div class="v_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with V</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Ban on sale / prohibition on encumbrance</a></h6>
              <p>This means that the owner can neither encumber the property (e.g. with a loan or usufruct) nor sell it or give it away without the consent of the beneficiary. The prohibition may, but need not, include both restrictions.</p>
              <p>The ban only becomes effective against any outsider once it has been entered in the land register. However, the ban on sale and encumbrance can only be entered in the land register if it is granted between spouses or between (grand)parents and (stepchildren, in-laws or grandchildren) children.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Market value</a></h6>
              <p>The price that is achieved under normal circumstances for the sale of an item (property) is called the market value.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Loss compensation</a></h6>
              <p>One speaks of loss compensation when losses can be offset against income from the same year for tax purposes. This reduces the tax base and therefore also the tax burden.</p>
              <p>Special regulations apply to the compensation of losses from the sale of real estate: They are primarily to be offset against profits from the sale of real estate.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Hidden defects</a></h6>
              <p>If you buy a property or move into one as a tenant and it turns out after some time that a major <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">hidden defect</a> has a negative impact on the quality or value of the property that was not immediately apparent - you have the possibility of making claims to ask for compensation. In the case of ownership, these depend on the property and whether the warranty period has expired. As a tenant, you canclaim <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">a rent reduction .</a></p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Power of Attorney</a></h6>
              <p>A power of attorney is the authority of one person to have another person act on their behalf. One also speaks of a “representative power”. When it comes to real estate, powers of attorney can be granted, for example, to carry out renovations or repair work, to find a new tenant, to buy or sell real estate.</p>
              <p>Powers of attorney are granted in writing or verbally, depending on the requirement. This means that it is basically free of form. However, some powers of attorney require certain forms, eg a written document signed by the person who is to be represented.</p>
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with W =====================-->
            <div class="w_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with W</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Passing on tenancy law</a></h6>
              <p>What happens if a landlord sells the property? Can the tenants stay in their apartment anyway? yes they may</p>
              <p>The buyer assumes the role of landlord and enters into all existing leases as such. Nothing changes for the tenants.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Right of withdrawal / right of withdrawal for real estate</a></h6>
              <p>Click here for a video that explains the right of withdrawal or the right of withdrawal for real estate.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Living space / floor space / usable space</a></h6>
              <p>The living space is the total floor space that the apartment or house has to offer, i.e. the total floor space of the premises. Areas outside of the apartment or house, such as the basement or storage room, do not count.</p>
              <P>The usable area is the area that can be used for the intended purpose. Traffic areas (e.g. entrances, stairwells, elevators, corridors) and functional areas (e.g. boiler room, machine rooms) are not included.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Right of Residence & Right of Use</a></h6>
              <p>The right of residence is a personal easement and allows the entitled person to live in someone else's home. It can be structuredas a right of use or as <a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">a usufruct right .</a></p>
              <p class="mb-0">If the right of residence refers to all habitable parts of the house and the person entitled to live in the building may use the building without restriction (e.g. also rent it out), there is a right of usufruct.</p>
              <p>The interpretation of the contract is decisive.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Residential property / Residential property contract</a></h6>
              Residential property is understood to mean the right in rem of a co-owner of a property to the exclusive use and sole disposal of a residential property. A written agreement of all co-owners is required for the justification - the apartment ownership contract.
            </div>
            <!--===================== Terms with Z =====================-->
            <div class="z_container mt-4">
              <div class="title w-100 ps-3 py-2 text-dark mb-3">Terms with Z</div>
              <a href="#back_to_overview#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline mb-3 d-block">Back to overview</a>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Civil division A co-owner can sue for division of the ideal co-ownership</a></h6>
              <p>with the division suit. The result is that the community of owners is dissolved. The division can take place in two ways: real division (also natural division) or civil division.</p>
              <p>The civil division is the sale of the property and division of the proceeds according to the respective shares.</p>
              <h6 class="mb-4"><a href="#" class="a_color text-decoration-underline" target="_blank">Foreclosure of real estate in Austria</a></h6>
              <p>Foreclosure of real estate occurs when the previous owner has debts for which he is persistently unable to pay. The capital raised through the auction is used to pay off debts with creditors, the bank, etc.</p>
              <p>While the seller can demand a certain price for a "normal" real estate purchase and supply and demand regulate this, the owner who is in debt has no influence on the pricing at the auction.</p>
            </div>
